  "A hospital wants to test whether a new pain reliever works better than the current standard medication after knee surgery. They enroll 150 patients and randomly assign 75 to the new drug and 75 to the existing drug. Why did they use an active control instead of a placebo?": "",
  "To save money on the experiment": "",
  "Because withholding pain medication from surgery patients would be unethical": "",
  "Because placebos never work in pain studies": "",
  "To increase the sample size of the study": "",
  "When effective treatments already exist, it is unethical to withhold them by giving patients a placebo. An active control ensures all participants receive some level of pain relief.": "",
  "A tech company randomly assigns 500 website visitors to see either a blue 'Buy Now' button (Group A) or a green 'Buy Now' button (Group B). Group A has a 4.2% purchase rate and Group B has a 3.8% purchase rate. The difference is not statistically significant (p = 0.31). What should the company conclude?": "",
  "The experiment was poorly designed and should be discarded": "",
  "There is not enough evidence that button color affects purchase rates": "",
  "The green button should be used because it costs less": "",
  "The blue button is definitively better and should be used": "",
  "With a p-value of 0.31, the 0.4 percentage point difference could easily be due to random variation. There is insufficient evidence to conclude that button color meaningfully impacts purchase rates.": "",
  "A researcher wants to test the effect of study music on exam performance. She has 100 students from two dorms: 50 freshmen in Dorm A and 50 seniors in Dorm B. She randomly assigns half the freshmen to music and half to silence, and does the same for seniors. What advantage does this approach have over a completely randomized design?": "",
  "It allows subjects to choose their treatment": "",
  "It eliminates the need for a control group": "",
  "It uses a larger sample size": "",
  "It blocks on class year, reducing variability caused by differences between freshmen and seniors": "",
  "By blocking on class year, the researcher controls for potential differences in academic experience between freshmen and seniors, reducing variability and increasing the power to detect a music effect.": "",
  "A farmer randomly assigns 60 plots of land to one of three irrigation methods (20 plots each). After harvest, Method C produces 15% more yield than Methods A and B. However, a colleague points out that the plots assigned to Method C happen to be closer to a river. What problem does this illustrate?": "",
  "The sample size was too small to yield a statistically significant difference between the methods": "",
  "The study lacked a placebo group, so the Hawthorne effect may have influenced the crop yields": "",
  "A confounding variable (proximity to the river) may explain the yield difference rather than the irrigation method": "",
  "The farmer should have used a matched-pairs design to compare each plot against its own baseline": "",
  "Even with randomization, chance imbalances can occur. The plots near the river have better water access, confounding the comparison. A blocked design controlling for river proximity would have been better.": "",
  "A new drug is compared to both a placebo and the standard drug for treating high cholesterol. 300 patients are randomly assigned to three groups of 100. After 6 months, the new drug lowers cholesterol by 25 mg/dL, the standard drug by 20 mg/dL, and the placebo by 3 mg/dL. How many groups and types of controls does this study have?": "",
  "2 groups: treatment and control": "",
  "3 groups but no control group": "",
  "3 groups: new drug (treatment), standard drug (active control), and placebo (placebo control)": "",
  "1 group with multiple measurements": "",
  "The study has three groups with two types of controls: the standard drug serves as an active control and the placebo serves as a placebo control, allowing comparison on both absolute effectiveness and relative effectiveness.": "",
  "An education researcher randomly assigns 200 students to either a traditional lecture format or a flipped classroom format. At the end of the semester, the flipped classroom group scores 8 points higher on the final exam (p = 0.003). Can the researcher conclude that the flipped classroom caused the higher scores?": "",
  "No, because this was only an observational study": "",
  "No, because 200 students is not enough": "",
  "Yes, but only if the study was double-blind": "",
  "Yes, because random assignment was used and the result is statistically significant": "",
  "Because students were randomly assigned to groups and the result is statistically significant (p = 0.003), the researcher can reasonably conclude that the flipped classroom format caused the improvement in scores.": "",
  "A cosmetics company claims its new sunscreen is better than the leading brand. They recruit 80 volunteers who apply one sunscreen on their left arm and the other on their right arm (randomly assigned). After UV exposure, they compare sunburn levels on each arm. What type of design is this?": "",
  "A randomized block design": "",
  "A completely randomized design": "",
  "An observational study": "",
  "A matched-pairs design where each person serves as their own control": "",
  "This is a matched-pairs design because each participant serves as their own control, with one arm receiving each treatment. This eliminates between-subject variability in skin type.": "",
  "A gym offers a free trial of a new workout program. Of the 300 members who sign up, 200 attend regularly and 100 drop out early. The 200 who stayed show significant fitness improvements. The gym advertises: 'Our program improves fitness in 100% of participants!' What is the problem with this claim?": "",
  "Fitness cannot be measured objectively": "",
  "The gym should have used a placebo workout": "",
  "The claim ignores the 100 who dropped out, introducing survivorship bias and self-selection": "",
  "The 300 participants is too small a sample": "",
  "By ignoring the 100 dropouts, the gym only reports results from the most committed members. This survivorship bias and self-selection make the claim misleading.": "",
  "A cereal company claims that children who eat their cereal every morning score higher on standardized tests. They surveyed 10,000 families and found a positive association. A statistician points out that this study lacks random assignment. What does this mean for the company's claim?": "",
  "The claim is valid because 10,000 is a sufficient sample for any conclusion": "",
  "The claim is valid because of the large sample size": "",
  "Random assignment is not needed for studies about nutrition": "",
  "The association may be caused by confounding variables like household income and parental involvement, not the cereal itself": "",
  "Without random assignment, confounders like family income, parental education, and access to resources could explain the association. A large sample does not compensate for lack of random assignment.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company tests a new allergy medication using 240 participants. They randomly assign 80 to the new drug, 80 to an existing allergy drug, and 80 to a placebo pill. Neither the participants nor the doctors evaluating symptoms know which pill each patient receives. After 4 weeks, the new drug group reports 40% fewer symptoms than the placebo group and 15% fewer than the existing drug group. Identify all the experimental design elements present in this study.": "",
